Disease: 47, XXX (Trisomy X) is a condition where a female has an extra X chromosome. This can lead to taller stature, learning difficulties, and developmental delays.
Symptoms: Taller than average height, learning disabilities, speech and language development delays.
Causes: An extra X chromosome in each cell of a female.
Treatment: Speech therapy, educational support, counseling.
Diagnosis: Chromosomal analysis through a blood test.
Prevention: There is no known prevention as it is a genetic condition.
Side effects: Potential for social and psychological effects due to learning disabilities.
Complications: Fertility issues, delayed development of motor skills.

Disease: 47, XXY (Klinefelter Syndrome) is a genetic condition in males caused by an extra X chromosome. It can result in reduced muscle mass, facial hair, and body hair, and can affect physical and cognitive development.
Symptoms: Low testosterone, reduced muscle mass, reduced facial and body hair, breast enlargement.
Causes: An extra X chromosome in males.
Treatment: Testosterone replacement therapy, physical therapy, speech and language therapy.
Diagnosis: Karyotype test, hormone testing.
Prevention: There is no known prevention as it is a genetic condition.
Side effects: Potential emotional and social challenges.
Complications: Increased risk of breast cancer, metabolic syndrome, and osteoporosis.

Disease: 48, XXYY Syndrome is a rare chromosomal disorder in males that includes an extra X and Y chromosome. Symptoms can include intellectual disability, behavioral issues, and physical abnormalities.
Symptoms: Intellectual disability, behavioral problems, physical abnormalities.
Causes: An extra X and Y chromosome in males.
Treatment: Supportive therapies including educational support, behavioral therapy, and medical management.
Diagnosis: Karyotype analysis.
Prevention: There is no known prevention as it is a genetic condition.
Side effects: Social and psychological impacts due to behavioral and intellectual challenges.
Complications: Potential heart defects, undescended testes, increased risk of autoimmune disorders.

Disease: 5,10-Methenyltetrahydrofolate Synthetase Deficiency is a rare metabolic disorder affecting the synthesis of certain amino acids, leading to developmental delays and neurological issues.
Symptoms: Developmental delays, neurological issues, seizures.
Causes: Genetic mutations affecting folate metabolism.
Treatment: Folate supplementation, anticonvulsants for seizures.
Diagnosis: Genetic testing, metabolic testing.
Prevention: There is no known prevention as it is a genetic condition.
Side effects: Potential side effects from medications used in treatment.
Complications: Severe developmental delays, neurological deterioration.
